# tcat does not deal with unicode

Not a minimal example, clearly.

-- input --
input | len(in) | runeLen | sWidth
cat | 3 | 3 | 3
some cats: 🐱, 😹, 😼 | 27 | 18 | 21
zaz: ẑa𝜔 | 13 | 8 | 8
lateen: lâtêên | 17 | 14 | 14
lâtêên | 9 | 6 | 6
math: 𝐀⟍⟪𝔹𝛈⊋⦰ | 30 | 13 | 13
wc: 🚾 | 8 | 5 | 6
🍔 | 4 | 1 | 2
-- want-with-pipes --
input                 | len(in) | runeLen | sWidth
cat                   | 3       | 3       | 3
some cats: 🐱, 😹, 😼 | 27      | 18      | 21
zaz: ẑa𝜔              | 13      | 8       | 8
lateen: lâtêên        | 17      | 14      | 14
lâtêên                | 9       | 6       | 6
math: 𝐀⟍⟪𝔹𝛈⊋⦰         | 30      | 13      | 13
wc: 🚾                | 8       | 5       | 6
🍔                    | 4       | 1       | 2
-- want-sans-pipes --
input                    len(in)    runeLen    sWidth
cat                      3          3          3
some cats: 🐱, 😹, 😼    27         18         21
zaz: ẑa𝜔                 13         8          8
lateen: lâtêên           17         14         14
lâtêên                   9          6          6
math: 𝐀⟍⟪𝔹𝛈⊋⦰            30         13         13
wc: 🚾                   8          5          6
🍔                       4          1          2
-- got --
input                 len(in)    runeLen    sWidth
cat                   3          3          3
some cats: 🐱, 😹, 😼    27         18         21
zaz: ẑa𝜔              13         8          8
lateen: lâtêên        17         14         14
lâtêên                9          6          6
math: 𝐀⟍⟪𝔹𝛈⊋⦰         30         13         13
wc: 🚾                 8          5          6
🍔                     4          1          2
END--END--END--END--END--END--END--END--END--END

# option to leave separator in output

I often want the pipe character left in the output (and I usually use
tcat to display pipe-separated files).

(Thinking now... I think my tcat does have an option for specifying an
output separator?  Maybe I could make it more ergonomic.)

